title.narrative: HEALTH SERVICES DELIVERY

description.narrative: National and provincial health authorities in selected provinces have improved capacity to plan, implement, monitor and report the delivery of gender-responsive MNCAH services, focused on the most disadvantaged, to prevent excess morbidity and mortality among girls, boys and women, including in humanitarian situations., which contributes to Cross Sectoral - Children With Disabilities, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Supply And Logistics. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Communities, parents, caregivers and children have increased awareness of the consequences of violence and have the skills to protect children and women.

description.narrative: In 2021, more than 67,100 newborns and their mothers were reached with an integrated package of MNCAH interventions resulting from scaling up EENC programme to 22 provinces.;125healthworkers to have their skills improved for EENC service delivery and 41,030 have received skin to skin careMore than 110,000 children were benefited with lifesaving routine vaccines (penta3 vaccination completed) and 356,000 doses of COVID-19 vaccines were administered to target beneficiaries in 22 provinces.
